<section xml:id="sec-4-7-ch04-exercises" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Exercises</title>
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using contraposition for the following prove for every integer <m>a</m> that
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    if <m>a</m> is even then <m>a+1</m> is odd
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    if <m>a</m> is odd then <m>a+2</m> is odd
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    if <m>a^2</m> is not divisible by 4 then <m>a</m> is odd
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using contradiction for the following prove for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> that
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    if <m>ab</m> is odd then both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are odd
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    if <m>a</m> is odd then <m>a+1</m> is even.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Using proof by cases for the following prove for any integer <m>a</m> that
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If 5 does not divide <m>a</m> then 5 does not divide <m>a^2</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>a(a-1)</m> is even
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>2a-1</m> is odd
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>a^2+a+3</m> is odd
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Prove the following biconditional statments for any integers <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, <m>c</m>, and <m>d</m> (you are allowed to divide for this exercise)
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>a</m> is odd if and only if <m>a+1</m> is even
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>ac|bc</m> if and only if <m>a|b</m> 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>a+c=b</m> and <m>2b-a=d</m> if and only if <m>a=b-c</m> and <m>b+c=d</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Prove the following statements involving existential
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    For any integer <m>a</m> there exists an unique integer <m>b</m> so that <m>a+b=0</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    There exists a rational number <m>x</m> such that <m>x+\frac{3}{2}=4</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Prove that <m>\sqrt{3}</m> is not a rational number.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
